{"aid": "40279864", "title": "Boeing faces new probe over 787 inspection doubts", "url": "https://www.bbc.com/news/business-68966894", "domain": "bbc.com", "votes": 10, "user": "edward", "posted_at": "2024-05-06 21:46:16", "comments": 0, "source_title": "Boeing faces new probe over 787 inspection doubts", "source_text": "Boeing faces new probe over 787 inspection doubts\n\n# Boeing faces new probe over 787 inspection doubts\n\n2 hours ago\n\nBy Natalie Sherman,Business reporter, New York\n\nGetty Images\n\nThe US has opened a new probe of troubled jet firm Boeing, after the company\ntold air safety regulators that it might not have properly inspected its 787\nDreamliner planes.\n\nThe Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) said it would look into whether\nstaff had falsified records.\n\nIt said Boeing was reinspecting all 787 jets still on the manufacturing line.\n\nBoeing will be forced to develop an \"action plan\" to address concerns about\nplanes already in service, it added.\n\nBoeing did not comment.\n\nInternally, it told staff that the \"misconduct\" had not created an \"immediate\nsafety of flight issue\", according to a message seen by the Wall Street\nJournal, which first reported the investigation.\n\nShares in the company fell more than 1% after the investigation was announced.\n\nThe FAA said that Boeing had come forward \"voluntarily\" last month to warn\nthat it \"may not have completed\" inspections required to confirm adequate\nelectrical safeguards where the wings join the main body of certain of its 787\nDreamliners, a large jet often used on international flights.\n\n\"The FAA is investigating whether Boeing completed the inspections and whether\ncompany employees may have falsified aircraft records,\" it said.\n\n\"As the investigation continues, the FAA will take any necessary action - as\nalways - to ensure the safety of the flying public.\"\n\nIt is the latest problem to erupt at Boeing since January, when an unused\nemergency exit door blew off a new 737 Max 9 plane shortly after take-off,\nthrusting its manufacturing and safety processes into the spotlight.\n\nThe incident prompted the temporary grounding of dozens of planes and has\nforced the firm to drastically slow production, while sparking increased\nregulatory oversight, criminal investigation and other legal and financial\ntroubles.\n\nIn March, chief executive Dave Calhoun said he would be stepping down by the\nend of the year, becoming the most high-profile person to exit the company in\nthe wake of the incident.\n\nLast month, Congress hosted a hearing featuring whistleblowers, including Sam\nSalehpour who testified that his concerns about the 787 were dismissed.\n\nBoeing has said it is working to reform its corporate culture to encourage\npeople who see problems to speak out, with a \"more than 500% increase\" in\nreports from employees since January.\n\n## Boeing whistleblower says he was put through 'hell'\n\n## How much trouble is Boeing in?\n\nCompanies\n\nBoeing\n\nInternational Business\n\nAir travel\n\nRelated\n\n## Apple sales fall in nearly all countries\n\n4 days ago\n\nBusiness\n\n## Weight loss drug wins 25,000 new US users a week\n\n4 days ago\n\nBusiness\n\n## J&J hopes for deal with third talc settlement\n\n5 days ago\n\nMore\n\n21 hrs ago\n\n## Qantas agrees payouts over 'ghost flights'\n\nQantas agrees to pay millions to settle lawsuit accusing it of selling tickets\nto cancelled flights.\n\n21 hrs ago\n\nBusiness\n\n3 days ago\n\n## Have the wheels come off for Tesla?\n\nAs the electric carmaker sees sales fall and cuts jobs, we take a closer look\nat its problems.\n\n3 days ago\n\nBusiness\n\n4 days ago\n\n## How the computer games industry is embracing AI\n\nDeveloping computer games can be wildly expensive so some hope that AI can cut\nthe cost.\n\n4 days ago\n\nBusiness\n\n5 days ago\n\n## Uber faces \u00a3250m London black cab drivers case\n\nThe case against the US-based ride-hailing giant is being brought on behal